\title{Diffdock}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Diffusion-based molecular docking. Predict protein-ligand binding poses from PDB/SMILES, confidence scores, virtual screening, for structure-based drug design. Not for affinity prediction."}

\subtree{
\title{DiffDock: Molecular Docking with Diffusion Models}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{DiffDock is a diffusion-based deep learning tool for molecular docking that predicts 3D binding poses of small molecule ligands to protein targets. It represents the state-of-the-art in computational docking, crucial for structure-based drug discovery and chemical biology.}

\p{\strong{Core Capabilities:}}

\ul{
\li{Predict ligand binding poses with high accuracy using deep learning}
\li{Support protein structures (PDB files) or sequences (via ESMFold)}
\li{Process single complexes or batch virtual screening campaigns}
\li{Generate confidence scores to assess prediction reliability}
\li{Handle diverse ligand inputs (SMILES, SDF, MOL2)}
}

\p{\strong{Key Distinction:} DiffDock predicts \strong{binding poses} (3D structure) and \strong{confidence} (prediction certainty), NOT binding affinity (ΔG, Kd). Always combine with scoring functions (GNINA, MM/GBSA) for affinity assessment.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\p{This skill should be used when:}

\ul{
\li{"Dock this ligand to a protein" or "predict binding pose"}
\li{"Run molecular docking" or "perform protein-ligand docking"}
\li{"Virtual screening" or "screen compound library"}
\li{"Where does this molecule bind?" or "predict binding site"}
\li{Structure-based drug design or lead optimization tasks}
\li{Tasks involving PDB files + SMILES strings or ligand structures}
\li{Batch docking of multiple protein-ligand pairs}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Installation and Environment Setup}
\subtree{
\title{Check Environment Status}
\p{Before proceeding with DiffDock tasks, verify the environment setup:}

\pre{\startverb
# Use the provided setup checker
python scripts/setup_check.py
\stopverb}

\p{This script validates Python version, PyTorch with CUDA, PyTorch Geometric, RDKit, ESM, and other dependencies.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Installation Options}
\p{\strong{Option 1: Conda (Recommended)}}

\pre{\startverb
git clone https://github.com/gcorso/DiffDock.git
cd DiffDock
conda env create --file environment.yml
conda activate diffdock
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Option 2: Docker}}

\pre{\startverb
docker pull rbgcsail/diffdock
docker run -it --gpus all --entrypoint /bin/bash rbgcsail/diffdock
micromamba activate diffdock
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Important Notes:}}

\ul{
\li{GPU strongly recommended (10-100x speedup vs CPU)}
\li{First run pre-computes SO(2)/SO(3) lookup tables (~2-5 minutes)}
\li{Model checkpoints (~500MB) download automatically if not present}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Workflows}
\subtree{
\title{Workflow 1: Single Protein-Ligand Docking}
\p{\strong{Use Case:} Dock one ligand to one protein target}

\p{\strong{Input Requirements:}}

\ul{
\li{Protein: PDB file OR amino acid sequence}
\li{Ligand: SMILES string OR structure file (SDF/MOL2)}
}

\p{\strong{Command:}}

\pre{\startverb
python -m inference \
  --config default_inference_args.yaml \
  --protein_path protein.pdb \
  --ligand "CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O" \
  --out_dir results/single_docking/
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Alternative (protein sequence):}}

\pre{\startverb
python -m inference \
  --config default_inference_args.yaml \
  --protein_sequence "MSKGEELFTGVVPILVELDGDVNGHKF..." \
  --ligand ligand.sdf \
  --out_dir results/sequence_docking/
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Output Structure:}}

\pre{\startverb
results/single_docking/
├── rank_1.sdf          # Top-ranked pose
├── rank_2.sdf          # Second-ranked pose
├── ...
├── rank_10.sdf         # 10th pose (default: 10 samples)
└── confidence_scores.txt
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow 2: Batch Processing Multiple Complexes}
\p{\strong{Use Case:} Dock multiple ligands to proteins, virtual screening campaigns}

\p{\strong{Step 1: Prepare Batch CSV}}

\p{Use the provided script to create or validate batch input:}

\pre{\startverb
# Create template
python scripts/prepare_batch_csv.py --create --output batch_input.csv

# Validate existing CSV
python scripts/prepare_batch_csv.py my_input.csv --validate
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{CSV Format:}}

\pre{\startverb
complex_name,protein_path,ligand_description,protein_sequence
complex1,protein1.pdb,CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O,
complex2,,COc1ccc(C#N)cc1,MSKGEELFT...
complex3,protein3.pdb,ligand3.sdf,
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Required Columns:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb complex_name\stopverb}: Unique identifier}
\li{\code{\startverb protein_path\stopverb}: PDB file path (leave empty if using sequence)}
\li{\code{\startverb ligand_description\stopverb}: SMILES string or ligand file path}
\li{\code{\startverb protein_sequence\stopverb}: Amino acid sequence (leave empty if using PDB)}
}

\p{\strong{Step 2: Run Batch Docking}}

\pre{\startverb
python -m inference \
  --config default_inference_args.yaml \
  --protein_ligand_csv batch_input.csv \
  --out_dir results/batch/ \
  --batch_size 10
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{For Large Virtual Screening (>100 compounds):}}

\p{Pre-compute protein embeddings for faster processing:}

\pre{\startverb
# Pre-compute embeddings
python datasets/esm_embedding_preparation.py \
  --protein_ligand_csv screening_input.csv \
  --out_file protein_embeddings.pt

# Run with pre-computed embeddings
python -m inference \
  --config default_inference_args.yaml \
  --protein_ligand_csv screening_input.csv \
  --esm_embeddings_path protein_embeddings.pt \
  --out_dir results/screening/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow 3: Analyzing Results}
\p{After docking completes, analyze confidence scores and rank predictions:}

\pre{\startverb
# Analyze all results
python scripts/analyze_results.py results/batch/

# Show top 5 per complex
python scripts/analyze_results.py results/batch/ --top 5

# Filter by confidence threshold
python scripts/analyze_results.py results/batch/ --threshold 0.0

# Export to CSV
python scripts/analyze_results.py results/batch/ --export summary.csv

# Show top 20 predictions across all complexes
python scripts/analyze_results.py results/batch/ --best 20
\stopverb}

\p{The analysis script:}

\ul{
\li{Parses confidence scores from all predictions}
\li{Classifies as High (>0), Moderate (-1.5 to 0), or Low (<-1.5)}
\li{Ranks predictions within and across complexes}
\li{Generates statistical summaries}
\li{Exports results to CSV for downstream analysis}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Confidence Score Interpretation}
\p{\strong{Understanding Scores:}}

\pre{\startverb
| Score Range | Confidence Level | Interpretation |
|------------|------------------|----------------|
| **> 0** | High | Strong prediction, likely accurate |
| **-1.5 to 0** | Moderate | Reasonable prediction, validate carefully |
| **< -1.5** | Low | Uncertain prediction, requires validation |
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Critical Notes:}}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Confidence ≠ Affinity}: High confidence means model certainty about structure, NOT strong binding}
\li{\strong{Context Matters}: Adjust expectations for:}
\li{Large ligands (>500 Da): Lower confidence expected}
\li{Multiple protein chains: May decrease confidence}
\li{Novel protein families: May underperform}
\li{\strong{Multiple Samples}: Review top 3-5 predictions, look for consensus}
}

\p{\strong{For detailed guidance:} Read \code{\startverb references/confidence_and_limitations.md\stopverb} using the Read tool}
}

\subtree{
\title{Parameter Customization}
\subtree{
\title{Using Custom Configuration}
\p{Create custom configuration for specific use cases:}

\pre{\startverb
# Copy template
cp assets/custom_inference_config.yaml my_config.yaml

# Edit parameters (see template for presets)
# Then run with custom config
python -m inference \
  --config my_config.yaml \
  --protein_ligand_csv input.csv \
  --out_dir results/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Key Parameters to Adjust}
\p{\strong{Sampling Density:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb samples_per_complex: 10\stopverb} → Increase to 20-40 for difficult cases}
\li{More samples = better coverage but longer runtime}
}

\p{\strong{Inference Steps:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb inference_steps: 20\stopverb} → Increase to 25-30 for higher accuracy}
\li{More steps = potentially better quality but slower}
}

\p{\strong{Temperature Parameters (control diversity):}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb temp_sampling_tor: 7.04\stopverb} → Increase for flexible ligands (8-10)}
\li{\code{\startverb temp_sampling_tor: 7.04\stopverb} → Decrease for rigid ligands (5-6)}
\li{Higher temperature = more diverse poses}
}

\p{\strong{Presets Available in Template:}}

\ol{
\li{High Accuracy: More samples + steps, lower temperature}
\li{Fast Screening: Fewer samples, faster}
\li{Flexible Ligands: Increased torsion temperature}
\li{Rigid Ligands: Decreased torsion temperature}
}

\p{\strong{For complete parameter reference:} Read \code{\startverb references/parameters_reference.md\stopverb} using the Read tool}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Advanced Techniques}
\subtree{
\title{Ensemble Docking (Protein Flexibility)}
\p{For proteins with known flexibility, dock to multiple conformations:}

\pre{\startverb
# Create ensemble CSV
import pandas as pd

conformations = ["conf1.pdb", "conf2.pdb", "conf3.pdb"]
ligand = "CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O"

data = {
    "complex_name": [f"ensemble_{i}" for i in range(len(conformations))],
    "protein_path": conformations,
    "ligand_description": [ligand] * len(conformations),
    "protein_sequence": [""] * len(conformations)
}

pd.DataFrame(data).to_csv("ensemble_input.csv", index=False)
\stopverb}

\p{Run docking with increased sampling:}

\pre{\startverb
python -m inference \
  --config default_inference_args.yaml \
  --protein_ligand_csv ensemble_input.csv \
  --samples_per_complex 20 \
  --out_dir results/ensemble/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Integration with Scoring Functions}
\p{DiffDock generates poses; combine with other tools for affinity:}

\p{\strong{GNINA (Fast neural network scoring):}}

\pre{\startverb
for pose in results/*.sdf; do
    gnina -r protein.pdb -l "$pose" --score_only
done
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{MM/GBSA (More accurate, slower):} Use AmberTools MMPBSA.py or gmx_MMPBSA after energy minimization}

\p{\strong{Free Energy Calculations (Most accurate):} Use OpenMM + OpenFE or GROMACS for FEP/TI calculations}

\p{\strong{Recommended Workflow:}}

\ol{
\li{DiffDock → Generate poses with confidence scores}
\li{Visual inspection → Check structural plausibility}
\li{GNINA or MM/GBSA → Rescore and rank by affinity}
\li{Experimental validation → Biochemical assays}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Limitations and Scope}
\p{\strong{DiffDock IS Designed For:}}

\ul{
\li{Small molecule ligands (typically 100-1000 Da)}
\li{Drug-like organic compounds}
\li{Small peptides (<20 residues)}
\li{Single or multi-chain proteins}
}

\p{\strong{DiffDock IS NOT Designed For:}}

\ul{
\li{Large biomolecules (protein-protein docking) → Use DiffDock-PP or AlphaFold-Multimer}
\li{Large peptides (>20 residues) → Use alternative methods}
\li{Covalent docking → Use specialized covalent docking tools}
\li{Binding affinity prediction → Combine with scoring functions}
\li{Membrane proteins → Not specifically trained, use with caution}
}

\p{\strong{For complete limitations:} Read \code{\startverb references/confidence_and_limitations.md\stopverb} using the Read tool}
}

\subtree{
\title{Troubleshooting}
\subtree{
\title{Common Issues}
\p{\strong{Issue: Low confidence scores across all predictions}}

\ul{
\li{Cause: Large/unusual ligands, unclear binding site, protein flexibility}
\li{Solution: Increase \code{\startverb samples_per_complex\stopverb} (20-40), try ensemble docking, validate protein structure}
}

\p{\strong{Issue: Out of memory errors}}

\ul{
\li{Cause: GPU memory insufficient for batch size}
\li{Solution: Reduce \code{\startverb --batch_size 2\stopverb} or process fewer complexes at once}
}

\p{\strong{Issue: Slow performance}}

\ul{
\li{Cause: Running on CPU instead of GPU}
\li{Solution: Verify CUDA with \code{\startverb python -c "import torch; print(torch.cuda.is_available())"\stopverb}, use GPU}
}

\p{\strong{Issue: Unrealistic binding poses}}

\ul{
\li{Cause: Poor protein preparation, ligand too large, wrong binding site}
\li{Solution: Check protein for missing residues, remove far waters, consider specifying binding site}
}

\p{\strong{Issue: "Module not found" errors}}

\ul{
\li{Cause: Missing dependencies or wrong environment}
\li{Solution: Run \code{\startverb python scripts/setup_check.py\stopverb} to diagnose}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Performance Optimization}
\p{\strong{For Best Results:}}

\ol{
\li{Use GPU (essential for practical use)}
\li{Pre-compute ESM embeddings for repeated protein use}
\li{Batch process multiple complexes together}
\li{Start with default parameters, then tune if needed}
\li{Validate protein structures (resolve missing residues)}
\li{Use canonical SMILES for ligands}
}
}
}

